        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The most important administrative records are the two volumes of vestry minutes dating from 1917 to 1923 and 1954 to 1968. Each of the volumes contains, in addition to minutes of the vestry, minutes of the bishop's committee records and of the annual parish meeting. The volume for the years 1954 to 1968 includes discussions the flight of many parishioners to the suburbs, the integration of minorities into the life of the parish, and specifics of the reversion of the church to mission status.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <c02 level="file">
          <did>
            <container type="box" label="Box [704529146322727655]">5</container>
            <unitdate type="inclusive" normal="1917/1923">1917-1923</unitdate></did>
          <odd>
            <p>(includes minutes of Annual Parish Meeting, treasurer's reports, and correspondence)</p>
          </odd>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="file">
          <did>
            <container type="box" label="Box [704529146322727655]">5</container>
            <unitdate type="inclusive" normal="1954/1968">1954-1968</unitdate></did>
          <odd>
            <p>(includes correspondence, senior warden's reports, and minutes of Bishop's Committee after reversion to mission status)</p>
          </odd>
        </c02>
      </c01>
      <c01 level="series">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Office files</unittitle>
        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The office files include a miscellanea of scattered minutes and administrative papers. Of particular interest is the folder of material for Allen Grey. Mr. Grey held an office in St. Thomas from 1947 to 1982 and for most of that time served as senior warden. His correspondence contains both letters received and carbon copies of letters sent. The latter reveal, in colorful language, the thoughts and activities of a man passionately committed to his church and deeply concerned with the welfare of his fellow parishioners. This series also contains an Inventory of Furnishings and Memorials, created in 1966 by Winifred Gerow, who is identified in the photograph album as the historian of St. Thomas. The inventory was originally kept in a three ring binder. It is arranged chronologically by the object's date of acquisition or donation. Each page contains a description of an item and often includes interesting footnotes pertaining to its use or influence on parishioners or giving personal information about the donors.</p>
        </scopecontent>
